issue.title: Capacity parser ENTSOE
issue.body:
## Issue

This is part of the outlier detection project where the aim is to flag data points that are above installed capacity. 
When possible, a capacity_parser will be developed so that we can update as many capacity configurations as possible can be updated automatically. 
We have managed to build parsers that will update 151 zones. The data is sourced from different authoritative sources such as: 
- [ENTSO-e](https://transparency.entsoe.eu/generation/r2/installedGenerationCapacityAggregation/show)
- [EMBER](https://ember-climate.org/)
- [EIA](https://www.eia.gov/electricity/data/eia860/)
- [IRENA](https://www.irena.org/Data/Downloads/IRENASTAT)

For zones or subzones that are not included, a specific parser can be built or the update will be done manually (draft documentation of the whole update process can be found [here](https://github.com/electricitymaps/electricitymaps-contrib/blob/md/capacity-update-process/CAPACITY_UPDATE.md))

The aim of this project is to enable collecting historical capacity so that the outlier detection can run on the whole time series. This is why the capacity configuration format is updated and follows the same structure as the emission factors configurations:
capacity
```
capacity
├── wind
    ├── datetime: "2023-01-01"
    ├── source: "ENTSOE"
    └── value: 5233
```

## Description

This PR includes a capacity parser for all ENTSOE zones

### Preview

![image](https://github.com/electricitymaps/electricitymaps-contrib/assets/107848894/d461773a-7871-4d68-ae4d-bce49361bbb6)


### Double check

- [ ] I have tested my parser changes locally with `poetry run test_parser "zone_key"`
- [ ] I have run `pnpx prettier --write .` and `poetry run format` to format my changes.

comment.body:

NP thanks for the heads up :)

pull_request.title: Fix Vietnam parser
pull_request.body:
## Issue

Closes #5775

## Description
This PR fixes the consumption and price parser for Vietnam using the endpoints explained in the issue. Unfortunately, the parser does not support the subzones. This is because the way the data is published in the live endpoint, data for 00:00 local time is never available. We can work around this using the historical data, but it is not available for subzones.

Please note that there is daily production data which could complement this consumption data also available.

### Preview

```
{'consumption': 28967.8,
  'datetime': datetime.datetime(2023, 10, 27, 5, 30, tzinfo=zoneinfo.ZoneInfo(key='Asia/Ho_Chi_Minh')),
  'source': 'nldc.evn.vn',
  'sourceType': <EventSourceType.measured: 'measured'>,
  'zoneKey': 'VN'}
```

### Double check

- [X] I have tested my parser changes locally with `poetry run test_parser "zone_key"`
- [X] I have run `pnpx prettier --write .` and `poetry run format` to format my changes.

pull_request.title: Set Node to v20
pull_request.body:
## Issue

Closes #5984 

(Although a wiki update will still be required once this is merged)

## Description

I'm new to this project and decided to take on this issue because I ran into it when I first setup this project. Sorry ahead of time for this long message, but I figure you'd appreciate seeing my reasoning.

First, I made **.npmrc** file changes, adding in the setting [use-node-version](https://pnpm.io/npmrc#use-node-version). This will make PNPM use Node v20.9.0 when running any package.json script. PNPM will actually download that version of Node if it does not detect it on the developer's machine. I tried to use a less specific version (e.g `use-node-version=20`), but then PNPM complained that this was not a correct format. An alternative approach would be to use the popular tool [NVM}(https://github.com/nvm-sh/nvm) along with adding new **.nvmrc** files, which does allow only specifying a major version. Also, I don't know if this is going to require changes or not in your CI environment.

Second, the issue we were seeing with running the project with Node 20 was simply caused by the fact that **ts-node** has not been updated since July 2022, and therefore it does not have a targeted configuration for running with ESM mode in Node 20. Indeed, there is a [long-standing open issue about this](https://github.com/TypeStrong/ts-node/issues/1997).

In the long issue thread, you will see that most people tackle this issue by running their script with `node --experimental-loader=ts-node/esm` (or `node --loader=ts-node/esm`, which is the same thing). However, this approach is discouraged in the Node 20 [CLI documentation](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest-v20.x/api/cli.html#--experimental-loadermodule). It also has the unpleasant side-effect of displaying a long warning in the terminal, which can only be disabled by turning off *all warnings* from Node. The good thing is that the warning message output the code that is now in the new file **web/scripts/register-tsNodeESM.js**, a module resolution hook, which allows us to use [the preferred `--import` flag](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest-v20.x/api/module.html#enabling).

Note that there is a [ts-node PR](https://github.com/TypeStrong/ts-node/pull/2073) which will add a similar hook to ts-node, hopefully in an upcoming release. Also, after no releases in a long time, ts-node had a [beta released last week for a new major version](https://github.com/TypeStrong/ts-node/issues/2077). So this script I added may not be needed for too long, but in the meanwhile I think it's good that we upgrade to the latest Node LTS.

### Double check

- [X] I have run `pnpx prettier --write .` and `poetry run format` to format my changes.

issue.title: county info ℹ️ button broken on mobile
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**


**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Go to any country with an info button in the app or browser (tested on my phone); e.g. https://app.electricitymaps.com/zone/CH?wind=true
2. Tap the `(i)` button at the top right
3. Nothing happens

**Expected behavior**
A dialog should've appeared with some important note about the displayed data.

**Smartphone (if relevant):**
 - OS: Android
 - Browser: Firefox; also reproduced in the app

comment.body: While I think it would be best to make the button work (on mobile) first, it's also worth asking if having a button with an icon is sufficient to communicate sometimes significant data caveats; if it's always been broken and nobody bothered reporting it up to now, it makes me wonder how many people actually read the information there.
